Corollary III.3. The AEU framework admits contin uous interpolation between area-law (α = 1 − 1/d) and volume-law (α = 1) scaling by varying the tensor network parameters. 
C. Consistency with physical constraints 
Several consistency checks are essential: 
Energy bounds. The construction must not require divergent energy density. We show in Appendix B that with appropriate scale-dependent couplings ϵs ∼ s−pfor p > γ + 1, the energy per site remains bounded. 
Causality. Since the tensor network is built on a spatial lattice and all operations respect locality, causality is preserved in the time-evolved system. 
Stability. The ground state of the constructed Hamil tonian is stable against local perturbations, as the hierar chical structure creates an energy gap at each scale. 
IV. LATTICE TENSOR-NETWORK MODEL 
We now construct an explicit lattice realization of the anti-holographic map using tensor networks. 
A. Network architecture 
Consider a 2D square lattice (generalizable to arbitrary d) with N = L × L sites. We construct a hierarchical network with depth S = log2 L. 
At each scale s, we place branching tensors T(s) of rank rs = 2bs + 1 connecting: 
• bs bonds to the previous scale (inputs), 
• bs bonds to the next scale (outputs), 
• 1 bond to a physical index at that scale. 

